The central highlands and south eastern lowlands are expected
to experience cooler conditions until July 16. Central highlands
include Nairobi, Nyandarua, Nyeri, Kirinyaga, Murang'a, Kiambu, Meru, Embu and
Tharaka Nithi. The areas are
expected to experience mainly cool and cloudy mornings with light
rains and short sunny intervals, with the possibility of rain in the afternoons or evenings. South eastern
lowlands, which include Kajiado, Kitui, Makueni, Machakos and Taita
Taveta are expected to have cool and cloudy mornings with sunny intervals. The nights are
expected to be partly cloudy. The weatherman that in the coastal strip, there will be morning and afternoon showers over a few places
throughout the forecast period. Evenings are
expected to be partly cloudy with the possibility of showers on some
days. North eastern areas - Marsabit, Mandera, Wajir, Garissa and Isiolo - are expected to
experience partly cloudy skies at night and sunny intervals during
the day throughout the forecast period. Northwestern
counties of Turkana, West Pokot, Samburu will have sunny intervals during the day and partly cloudy conditions at night. Afternoon or evening
showers and thunderstorms are, however, likely over a few places while
morning rains are likely at the boarder with Uganda next Monday. The Lake Victoria
basin, highlands west of the Rift Valley, central and south Rift
Valley are expected to experience rains over a few places and sunny
intervals in the mornings of Tuesday, Saturday and Monday. Afternoon or evening
showers and thunderstorms are expected over a few places throughout the
forecast period. These areas and the Coastal strip mainly recorded rainfall last week, the highest levels being in Butere. Mandera county recorded the highest daily maximum temperature of 35.5 degrees Celsius while Nyahururu recorded the lowest at 6.5 degrees Celsius. Click here for the latest political news